[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing json interpolator features**\n\nI'm considering the json interpolator and how existing ones cover many features, so I don’t want to duplicate their work. I'm thinking about a new feature that allows interpolation in string positions next to literal text. For instance, it could involve combining placeholders inside JSON string segments with other text. I really need to analyze the macro and ensure that all arguments are inserted as quoted placeholders, regardless of their position.\n\n**Exploring json interpolator limitations**\n\nI'm analyzing how the json interpolator works with strings and placeholders. For example, if I write a json string like `{\"message\":\"prefix $name suffix\"}`, I wonder if the interpolator manages this correctly. The macro might produce invalid JSON because the quotes around placeholders can lead to issues. In Scala, the quotes stay in place, resulting in problems with the insertion order and syntax.\n\nAlso, I'm considering potential features like allowing duplicate field keys in JSON. I'm unsure about that, though. It seems this feature could improve how we manage interpolated keys in various contexts!\n\n**Checking interpolated arrays and features**\n\nI'm thinking about arrays and how interpolated values can work alongside string values. The existing primitive collections only cover arguments as values within objects, not directly in arrays. I wonder if there's support for interpolated strings in arrays.\n\nI also need to identify features not previously covered, like the handling of negative exponents in jnum or issues with the parser for jnum fallbacks. I might also need to check upstream tests related to key interpolation—especially with custom key encoders, since I'm unsure how non-string keys fit into this context.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_030f37986272c8d3016a2acac51eec8194876bacab1fb8cd97\",\"type\